<TITLE> Climate Camp opens to sensitise people </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Noakhali, Oct 23 (bdnews24.com)A national camp on climate change began in Noakhali on Friday, for the first time in the country, to sensitise the people about the risks of climate change. Chief of All Party Parliamentary Group (AAPG) on Climate and Environment Saber Hossain Chowdhury stressed national unity to combat the climate change threats. Over 100 representatives from 51 districts and the SAARC countries joined the three-day Bangladesh Climate Camp. Programmes of the camp comprise workshops, discussions, signature collection and documentary film screening. Chowdhury said climate change is now the chief threat to national security. "It poses a stiff challenge to our food security, agriculture and education." Address the youths, the Awami League MP said, "Only the youths can raise consciousness among the people and unite them to fight the challenge." Local MP Ekramul Karim Chowdhury, vice chancellor of Noakhali University of Science and Technology Sanjay Kumar Odhikari, Oxfam Great Britain advocacy representative Kirsty Hius spoke, among others, in the opening session. Participatory Research and Action Network (PRAN), Youth in Action on Climate (YAC) and Oxfam International are organising the camp. bdnews24
